##How can the disease control system catch up when the virus is gone?

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

The following article comes from us to make up lessons, author Han Tan Qing

Adult 100,000 Whys, rediscover your curiosity about the world

Viruses have been around for billions of years and have long been an integral part of the ecosystem. It is more impossible to wipe them out than it is to wipe out all the bugs, this new outbreak of pneumonia is by no means the last battle between humans and the virus.

In fact, with the experience of the fight, the face of the virus is not as helpless as before, but after the disappearance of mental slack in the epidemic for the hands of the preparation of the foreshadowing. For example, in the SARS more than ten years ago, many valuable experiences were summarized, but not all of them were effectively implemented.

What loopholes have been exposed by this outbreak? How can we make up for it?

We need sentries on the ground who can spot an outbreak

Of course, there is no specific drug in the face of the virus, but if early detection of the epidemic, control of infection, isolation and treatment of infected people, often will be able to eliminate the epidemic in the embryonic state. What has done well in this area is Japan, where prevention surveillance reaches the "tip" through a tiered diagnosis and treatment system.

When people get sick in Japan, they usually go to specialist clinics. If the doctor at the clinic believes that the patient's condition needs to be diagnosed at a general hospital, he will write a letter of recommendation and make an appointment for the patient.

There are many benefits to this approach.

On the one hand, the specialized clinics scattered throughout the country constitute "nerve endings" , which are deeply rooted in society. They are able to quickly detect and report outbreaks as soon as they occur. The competent authorities monitor the epidemic trend according to the changes in the number of cases, the risk of infectious diseases and related preventive measures will be announced to the society.

On the other hand, this arrangement relieves the pressure of the General Hospital greatly, not only can let the public get medical treatment in time, but also optimizes the allocation of resources? Comprehensive hospitals with high-quality medical resources can spare no effort in treating critically ill patients. As a result, these hospitals are largely free of long queues, reducing the likelihood of cross-contamination during outbreaks due to high population density.

But this kind of decentralized medical system has extremely high request to the doctor's professional quality and the hospital management ability.

In addition to medical treatment, there are also special "health clinics" throughout Japan, responsible for the prevention of infectious diseases. Health Care Centers regularly spread knowledge of epidemic prevention in residential areas, schools and other places, starting with children, to help residents develop good living and health habits.

The problem in most countries is that insufficient investment in public health has led to inadequate pre-infectious disease prevention, which in turn has put enormous pressure on follow-up treatment. Many of the more perfect anti-epidemic system of developed countries, although the new crown disease found early, but not in a timely manner, with luck, resulting in the spread of the epidemic.

Communication needs to be smooth

To deal with the epidemic, the whole country is a chess game. Only when the information communication is smooth, can the whole society concentrate its strength to defeat the enemy.

In many countries, information does not circulate among health, environment, food and other departments, and among governments. The problem is that the detection of abnormal conditions is not timely, and there is always a lag somewhere, the focus of the epidemic research is also in a fragmented, low-level repetitive plight, which wasted the early opportunities.

The United States has set up a relatively sound infectious disease reporting system, can achieve the sharing of early outbreaks. Epidemic information is not only reported from the bottom up, but also shared among different professional departments.

In addition, health professionals also have access to information, such as the Epi-X, which was established in 2000 and has about 6,000 users from the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, local health departments and public health agencies, the platform provides a rapid reporting and professional exchange platform for each individual health professional in public health events.

Epidemic Prevention and the economy

At the end of June 2009, the United States had more cases of swine flu than Mexico and Canada combined, the world's second and third largest countries. The reason is that based on animal studies and human observations, this swine flu is fundamentally different from previous flu: It spreads slowly and has a low mortality rate. So the United States did not choose to devote its entire nation to a relatively minor threat of swine flu.

"More dangerous than the COVID-19 is the flu, which has affected millions of Americans, " USA Today wrote in its Covid-19, "but the flu is more deadly and more widespread. "

The U. S. decision is also due to the "cautionary tale. ".

In 1976, the United States vaccinated 42 million people without fully understanding the situation, and instead of swine flu, more than 30 people died from side effects of the vaccine, resulting in 3,917 claims against the government, with a total cost of $3.5 billion, universal vaccination against swine flu has become one of the biggest public health blunders of the 20th century in the United States.

This is also the root cause of the "Buddhist" treatment of the epidemic in some countries, especially those with highly externally dependent economies that are more afraid of huge economic losses than viruses. But the disease does not evolve on the basis of human will. The problem now is that the spread of the disease in countries that had previously taken a chance is beginning to cost more to control.

In Normal Times,

Wait until the arrival of the epidemic action is absolutely too late, only the usual time home, in the face of crisis can take their time.

Thanks to the progress of modern medicine and the development of the epidemic prevention system, many infectious diseases were eliminated in the embryonic stage. So why, more than a decade after SARS, are scientists scouring the country to find the source of the virus in Batcave? Because of the virus data, when a similar outbreak is encountered again, it will not be a black eye.

Infectious Disease Epidemic Prevention is indeed a thankless work, not only to sit on the bench for a long time, usually it is difficult to see obvious results, so often overlooked. After all, it seems "silly" to go into a bat cave in the middle of the mountains to study faeces in the absence of an outbreak. But in the event of an outbreak, it is these unremarkable people and the work they insist on doing that constitutes the last line of defense against the virus.

Of course, China's research on infectious diseases on the investment still needs to be improved. SARS in 2003, Ebola in 2015, bird flu in 2017 and this new crown are all BSL-3 pathogens that require high-security medical laboratories for research. Bsl-3 laboratories are generally available in medical schools and hospitals of all high-level universities in the United States to facilitate rapid clinical isolation of dangerous pathogens and subsequent basic research.

At present, there are only five BSL-3 laboratories in Chinese universities, which are capable of studying non-veterinary pathogens, including Wuhan University, Zhejiang University, National Sun Yat-sen University, Fudan University and China Medical University, both the scale and the scope of foreign exchange and cooperation are extremely limited, making it difficult to meet the needs of scientific research.

There is also a shortage of public health professionals. The CDC has only about 2,100 employees, and lacks a mix of medical, public health, informatics, and legal expertise.

The material reserve is particularly important

It is also important to secure adequate medical supplies. Lack of materials not only can not meet the needs of prevention and control, the life safety of front-line medical staff will also bring huge hidden dangers.

In Singapore, for example, in the case of SARS, questionnaires showed that health care workers were more worried about getting sick or inadvertently spreading the disease to family, friends and colleagues than they were under intense work pressure.

The health authorities in Singapore not only provide adequate protective equipment such as protective clothing, gloves and goggles, but also pay great attention to ensuring the quality of such equipment and provide appropriate personal protection training, has greatly increased the confidence of the medical staff.

In response to natural and man-made disasters, the United States has also set up an emergency rescue system -- The U. S. National Strategic Reserve (SNS) .

The government of the United States, in cooperation with experts and in the light of the current national conditions and medical conditions, determines the scope of the material reserve. In addition to basic personal equipment such as face masks and protective clothing, it also includes antibiotics, medicines, portable emergency medical equipment and so on, the reserve range is very comprehensive, and will continue to update the reserve varieties according to the research of professional departments, to ensure that it can meet emergency needs.

In addition, the United States designed a rapid response package, each 50 tons of emergency package, consisting of 130 standard containers, can be deployed within 12 hours to the site of the incident. They are stored in secret strategic locations within the United States near major transportation hubs and delivered by world-class commercial shipping partners. One emergency kit contains enough supplies to sustain hundreds of thousands of people for ten days of treatment and prevention.

Moreover, because of the expiration date of medical supplies, large reserves also impose a financial burden, and the United States cooperates with corporations as well as the government reserves. For those that are available on the market, the government and the enterprise enter into contracts that guarantee direct delivery in case of emergency, reducing the government's management expenses by utilizing the existing warehousing and supply networks of suppliers.

But even as the United States prepares, it faces a shortage of supplies in the face of a devastating epidemic. At this point, a complete manufacturing system and a strong supply chain is particularly important.

The new crown epidemic will eventually end, but we enjoy the beautiful spring time, can not "good scars forget pain. ". Because there has been no world-wide pandemic for a long time, countries have generally slackened, exposing many loopholes in the epidemic.

Until the mystery of the virus, which threatens US forever, the only way to hold our ground is to invest more in public health and build an efficient health surveillance and response system, it's an insurance policy for everyone.

Planning: The Committee on Remedial Economic Studies
